@node Chapter 1
@chapter Installing and Starting GNU APL

@node Section 1.1
@section Installing APL

APL is built and installed like this:

@itemize
@item download the tar file containing GNU APL, from
 @uref{ftp://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/apl} or from one of its mirrors
 (see @uref{http://www.gnu.org/prep/ftp.html}), and
 un-tar the file.

@item read (and follow) the instructions given in file README in the
 unpacked directory.
@end itemize

For the experienced, but impatient reader: it is the well-known sequence

@example
$ ./configure
$ make
$ sudo make install
@end example

On success, an executable file named 'apl' will have been produced
in the sub-directory 'src'.

File README contains further instructions about the installation GNU APL.

@node Section 1.2
@section Starting APL

Last things first: before explaining how to start APL, it is important to
 remember how to stop (i.e. exit) it. Neither @b{^C} nor @b{^D} will stop
APL - these serve other purposes. Instead, you leave APL with the command
 @b{)OFF} or @b{)off} (on a separate line) like this:

@example
      )OFF
@end example


If APL is computing a function (and possibly caught in an endless loop),
then you may have to press @b{^C} (this is called @i{ATTENTION} in APL) to
return to APL's command mode so that the @b{)OFF} command can be entered.
In some circumstances it may be necessary to press @b{^C} twice within a
short time interval (this is called @i{INTERRUPT} in APL).

Using the )OFF command will not automatically save your work, however, a
history of your GNU APL commands will have been preserved. Having that said,
APL is started like every other program - by entering its name and optional
command line parameters, for example:

@example
$ apl
@end example

or:

@example
$ apl -id 1001
@end example

GNU APL is script-able; a text file whose first line looks like this (assuming
the APL interpreter binary is called 'apl' and is located in the current
directory):

@example
#! ./apl 
@end example

or (if the APL interpreter binary is not in the current directory but in
/mypath/apl):

@example
#! /mypath/apl
@end example

The path to the 'apl' binary can be missing (like in the first example),
relative, or absolute (second example). The exact details of how the first
line of a GNU APL script shall look vary slightly among operating systems.
Please consult the info (or man) pages for 'path_resolution' and/or 'execve'
on your operating system. After the name of the binary, optional GNU APL
command line options, usually --script, can be provided.

The text file must, of course, have execute permission, and should be ASCII
or, more likely, UTF-8 encoded. The APL characters in the script shall be
those defined in the Unicode character set (most of them in the U+2200 -
U+23FF range).

@node Section 1.3
@section Command Line Options

GNU APL understands the following command line options:

@itemize @bullet

@item
@b{-C new_root}

perform chroot("new_root") followed by chdir("/"). This restricts the access
of the process running GNU APL to files in or below directory new_root, and
it also changes the current directory (which could have resided above
new_root before the chroot() was executed).

The -C option is intended to be a security feature for GNU APL interpreters
that are facing hostile environments such as the public Internet.

NOTES:
@itemize @bullet

@item
For -C to work, new_root needs to contain a minimal set of binaries, in
particular a shell, and possibly libraries needed by the shell. Consult
'info chroot invocation' for issues to consider and common pitfalls.

@item
GNU APL processes the -C option (i.e. it calls chroot("new_root")) before
all other command line options. As a consequence, file names in other command
line options of GNU APL are also affected by -C. That means that the file
names in command line options are being interpreted relative to new_root
and @b{not} relative to the current directory of the process that had
started GNU APL.

@item
GNU APL may automatically start other processes such as APserver and friends
after processing the -C option. These processes (and the libraries that they
depend on) should reside in the proper directory below new_root. For example,
with the default configuration of GNU APL, GNU APL installs itself in
/usr/local/bin and also expects APserver in the same directory. After -C
new_root, however, /usr/local/bin is no longer accessible and one would need
to copy /usr/local/bin/APserver to new_root/usr/local/bin/APserver

@item
Depending on your platform, the process using @b{-C} may need root privileges.

@end itemize

@item @code{--cfg}

show ./configure options that were used to configure GNU APL, and exit.

@item @b{--[no]Color}

start with ]COLOR ON [OFF].

@item
@b{--CPU_limit_secs sec}

set CPU time limit to @i{sec} seconds.

@item
@code{-d}

run the APL interpreter (or APL script) in the background (i.e. as a daemon).
For this to work you need to provide some input to the background process,
e.g. via the -f option.

@item
@code{--emacs}

run in (old) Emacs mode.

@item
@code{--emacs_arg arg}

run in (new) Emacs mode with argument arg.

@item
@code{--eval line}

evaluate one APL @i{line} and exit (-s without -f is implied). This option
can be given several times; in that case several lines will be executed in
command line order before GNU apl exits. Keep in mind that command line
options are normally processed by the shell before being passed to apl.
Therefore quoting the argument of --eval may often be necessary and it is
common wisdom to always quote the --eval argument.

@item
@code{-f file}

read input from @i{file} rather than from the keyboard. When the end of
the file is reached, input is switched back to the keyboard. 
If you want to terminate the APL interpreter after executing the file,
then use )OFF as last line in the file or include the --OFF option.

@item
@code{--gpl}

show GNU APL license (GPL) and exit.

@item
@code{-L wsname}

)LOAD wsname on start-up.

@item
@code{--LX expr}

execute @b{expr} first. The workspace behaves as if ⎕LX (latent
expression) were set to @b{expr} in the workspace. This can be used,
for example, to start the same workspace with different start-up values.

@item
@code{-h}, @code{--help}

print all command line options with a brief hint about what they do.

@item
@code{--id proc}

use processor ID proc for this interpreter. If no ID is provided, then the
first unused ID > 1000 is taken by this interpreter and the ID becomes used
as long as the interpreter runs. Processor IDs are used by shared variables
to identify share partners.

@item
@code{-l num}

turn logging facility @b{num} ON (provided that dynamic logging was
./configure'd). The logging facility 37 (start-up messages) is of particular
importance for troubleshooting and it works even if dynamic logging
was not ./configure'd.

@item
@code{--mem [memory-limit]}

tell the interpreter not to use more than memory-limit bytes of RAM. By
using this option, the user is fully responsible for ensuring that the
specified amount of memory will always be available. The following rules
should be observed.

The interpreter will exit at start-up if @code{-mem} is used and:

@itemize
@item the platform on which the interpreter runs has no /proc/meminfo, or
@item the platform has no /proc/sys/vm/overcommit_memory, or
@item /proc/sys/vm/overcommit_memory is not 2 (aka. 'never overcommit')
@end itemize

On GNU/Linux systems these conditions are normally satisfied, but the root
user has to set /proc/sys/vm/overcommit_memory to 2 which differs from the
default value 0 (aka. overcommit allowed).

If no memory-limit is given, then a memory-limit of 50% is used.

If a memory-limit is provided then it must have a unit of %, kB, MB, or GB.
If the unit is % then the limit is computed as that percentage (between 5%
and 95%) of parameter 'MemFree:' in /proc/meminfo. Otherwise the limit
is the given amount in kB, MB, or GB.

For example:

@itemize
@item @code{--mem}      (50% of MemFree: in /proc/meminfo are guaranteed)
@item @code{--mem 80%}  (80% of MemFree: in /proc/meminfo are guaranteed)
@item @code{--mem 5G}   (5 GB are guaranteed)
@end itemize

WARNING: The memory-limit is checked against parameter 'MemFree' in
/proc/meminfo when GNU APL starts, but this does not protect against
other processes consuming the available free memory sometime later.

If that happens (and according to the rules above the user has the
responsibility to prevent it), then ⎕WA becomes unreliable and the
interpreter may crash badly (i.e. without a WS FULL error, and without
any chance to )SAVE the workspace) when the available memory is exhausted.

@item
@code{--echoCIN}
copy the input line (after editing) to stdout. For creating session logs.

@item
@code{--noCIN}

do not echo stdin to stdout. Almost a must for scripting (unless you
intend to troubleshoot a script).

@item
@code{--to_COUT}

normally GNU APL writes its output to stderr (i.e. file descriptor 2) so that,
when GNU APL is started in a script, the output of the script appears on
stdout (i.e. file descriptor 1) while the output of GNU APL appears on stderr.

This option redirects the stderr output of GNU APL to stdout. The same effect
can be achieved with the option "OUTPUT-TO-COUT Yes" in a preferences file.

@item
@code{--tcp_port PORT}

this option starts GNU APL as a server that listens on TCP port PORT.
Every TCP connection accepted by the server forks a new GNU APL instance
which has its stdin, stdout, and stderr redirected to the TCP connection.

WARNING: This option is dangerous if PORT is directly exposed to the Internet!

@item
@code{--noCONT}

do not load a SETUP or CONTINUE workspace on start-up.

@item
@code{--OFF}

This option causes GNU APL to perform an automatic )OFF command after the
last line of the last input file (as per -f option) was executed.

@item
@code{--PW COLS}

set the initial value of ⎕PW to COLS (min. 30, max. 10000)

@item
@code{--[no]SV}

do [not] start APserver (a shared variable server) on start-up. This disables
communication with other workspaces or auxiliary processors through
shared variables.

@item
@code{-p N}

use profile number N in preferences files. A preference file may contain
several sets of settings for different purposes; the profile number selects
one of these sets.

@item
@code{--par pproc}

use processor parent ID pproc (default: no parent ID).

@item
@code{--rawCIN}

do not emit ESC sequences. Normally ESC sequences are emitted for colored
output and during line editing. In scripts, however, ESC sequences usually
are not wanted and can be turned off with this option.

@item
@code{-s}, @code{--script}

this option is an abbreviation for:
 @code{--silent} @code{--noCIN} @code{--noCONT} @code{-f -}
(which is a typical combination of options for APL scripts).

@item
@code{-q}, @code{--silent}

suppress printing of the GNU APL welcome message. Useful for scripts.

@item
@code{--safe}

disable shared variables and native functions

@item
@code{--show_bin_dir}

display the binary directory where, according to ./configure, the programs
apl, APserver, AP100, and AP210 are installed. Then exit.

@item
@code{--show_doc_dir}

display the directory where, according to ./configure, documentation files
for GNU APL are installed. Then exit.

@item
@code{--show_etc_dir}

display the system configuration directory where, according to ./configure,
the preferences file for GNU APL is installed. Then exit.

@item
@code{--show_lib_dir}

display the library directory where, according to ./configure, shared library
files and the workspaces shipped with GNU APL are installed. Then exit.

@item
@code{--show_src_dir}

display the source directory where, according to ./configure, GNU APL
was compiled. Then exit. This can be used, for example, by native functions
that are built outside the GNU APL source tree to find GNU APL header files
that are needed to compile the native function.

@item
@code{--show_all_dirs}

display all the directories above. Then exit.

@item
@code{-T testcases ...}
run testcases. Testcases are text files that contain both input to the APL
interpreter and the expected response from the interpreter. The output from
the interpreter is compared with the expected output in the testcase file(s)
and differences are marked. In addition a summary file is created that tells
whether or not each of the testcases was successful.

@item
@code{--TM mode}

test mode. This option specifies how the interpreter shall behave
when running a number of testcases (as specified with the @code{-T} option).

@code{--TM 0} (default) run all testcases and exit after the last testcase.

@code{--TM 1} like @code{--TM 0} if no error was detected.
However, if one of the testcases has failed, then the interpreter
does not exit so that the user can investigate the state of APL
(SI, variable values, etc.).

@code{--TM 2} like @code{--TM 1}, but stay in the interpreter even if
all testcases have passed. This can be useful for quickly bringing the
interpreter into a specific state and continue manual troubleshooting
from that state.

@code{--TM 3} like @code{--TM 1}, but stop testcase execution after the
first failed testcase (i.e. do not exit).

@code{--TM 4} like @code{--TM 3}, but exit after the first failed
testcase. This is useful for automatic regression tests, where no errors
are expected.

@item
@code{--TR}

executes test case files in random order.

@item
@code{--TS}

Normally, when the interpreter is run with the @code{T} option,
an existing summary.log file is overwritten without notice.
This option causes new test results to be appended to a possibly
existing summary.log instead of overwriting it.

@item
@code{-v}, @code{--version},

show version information and exit.

@item
@code{-u UID}

run as user with UID 0. This option can only be used by the root user (who
then wants to run as a different user).

@item
@code{-w milli}

wait milli milliseconds at start-up. Useful to give other programs that are
started together with this interpreter time to initialize themselves.

@item @code{|  +APPOPT|}
@item @code{| ++APPOPT ARG1|}
@item @code{|+++APPOPT ARG1 ARG2|}
@item ...

   Those command line options above that start with + are understood by the
   GNU APL binary and their arguments must follow the description given for
   them. In addition the interpreter also accepts command line options that
   start with +. However, these options are not checked by the interpreter
   in any way, but are merely copied to @b{⎕ARG} (see below). In these options,
   APPOPT, ARG1, ARG2, ... are arbitrary strings that should not contain any
   whitespace characters. The purpose of these options is to control aspects
   of the APL application from the command line.

@item
@code{-}

end of command line options for the interpreter. GNU APL provides the system
variable ⎕ARG that returns all command line options with which the GNU APL
interpreter was invoked (similar to variable argv in main(int argc,
char * argv[]) in C/C++). Option @code{-} can be used to separate command line
options for the APL interpreter from command line options understood by APL
applications.

Thus,

@code{(⎕ARG ⍳ ⊂'--') ↑ ⎕ARG} returns the options for the APL interpreter, while

@code{(⎕ARG ⍳ ⊂'--') ↓ ⎕ARG} returns the options for the APL application.

All command line options after @code{-} are ignored by the interpreter
(except for including them in ⎕ARG).

@end itemize

@node Section 1.4
@section Configuration File for GNU APL

The default values for some of the command line options discussed in the
previous section can be set in a configuration file for GNU APL. The name
of the configuration file is 'preferences' and it should live in one of
the following directories:

@itemize

@item
in the sub-directory gnu-apl.d of the system configuration directory, or

@item
in the sub-directory .config/gnu-apl of the user's home directory (as per
$HOME).

@end itemize

The system configuration directory is usually /etc or /usr/local/etc and is
configurable via @option{./configure --sysconfdir}. An empty (i.e. most
settings commented out) preferences file is also installed in the
system configuration directory when GNU APL is installed. You can edit
it, use it as a template or read it to see which options can be controlled.

If file 'preferences' exists in both directories, the settings in
$HOME/.config/gnu-apl/preferences override settings in, for example,
/etc/gnu-apl.d/preferences.

Command line options in turn override settings in 'preferences' files.

@node Section 1.5
@section File Names and Paths

The GNU APL interpreter is a binary file named 'apl'. It is usually
installed in directory /usr/bin/ or in /usr/local/bin/. The location
where 'apl' is installed can be changed via ./configure options
(see file INSTALL).

GNU APL understands 4 file types:

@enumerate
@item APL workspaces that can be manipulated with the )LOAD, )SAVE,
 )COPY, and )DROP commands. APL workspaces are XML files and must have a
 file extension of .xml to be accepted by GNU APL. APL workspaces can only
 be exchanged between machines that all run GNU APL.

@item APL exchange files can be manipulated with the )IN and )OUT
 commands. APL exchange files are text files in ⎕TF format defined by IBM
 (basically APL expressions that create variables or functions)
 and must have a file extension of .atf to be accepted by GNU APL.
 APL exchange files can be exchanged between machines running APL
 interpreters from different vendors. The ⎕TF format can be easily emulated
 on machines not providing compatible )IN and )OUT commands.

@item APL scripts consist of APL commands and APL expressions (including
 function definition via ∇) like they would be entered by the user.
 APL scripts should have a file extension of .apl but other extensions
 are also accepted by GNU APL. APL scripts are, for example, the files
 expected for the -f command line option. A workspace can be written in this
 format with the )DUMP command and can become an active workspace using the
 )LOAD command.

@item APL testcase files are similar to APL scripts, but in addition to
 the APL commands and expressions they also contain the expected output
 from the commands.
 APL testcase files normally have a file extension of .tc for normal
 (functional) testcases and .pt for performance testcases.
 APL testcase files are, for example, the files expected for the
 -T command line option.

@end enumerate

The following APL commands are related to file names:

)LOAD [lib] name[.xml|.apl]

)SAVE [lib] [name[.xml]]

)COPY [lib] [name[.xml|.apl]]

)PCOPY [lib] [name[.xml|.apl]]

)DROP [lib] [name[.xml|.apl]]

)IN   [lib] name[.atf]

)PIN   [lib] name[.atf]

)OUT  [lib] name[.atf]

)DUMP [lib] [name[.apl]]

)LIB  [lib]

)LIBS [new-lib-root]

)WSID       [name]

The rules for how file names are constructed from the argument(s) of an APL
command are:

@enumerate
@item command arguments shown in brackets are optional.

@item lib is a number from 0 to 9. If lib is not present then 0 is taken
as default.

@item if the name is optional and missing then the workspace ID (the name
set with the )WSID command) is used.

@item if the file extension (i.e. .xml or .atf) is missing then it is
appended automatically to name.
@end enumerate

If the name starts with '/' then it is taken as an absolute path to
the file (an absolute file name) and no further computation is done
with the name.

Otherwise name is a relative path which is relative to some directory
library-root and a sub-directory of library-root that is determined by
the lib number. The library numbers 0-9 correspond to the following
directories:

    0: library-root/workspaces/

    1: library-root/wslib1/

    2: library-root/wslib2/

    ...

    9: library-root/wslib9/

The command )LIBS without arguments shows the mapping between library
numbers and paths. The command )LIBS with an argument sets a new lib-root.

The command )LIB [lib] shows the files in library (i.e. directory) lib.

The directory library-root is computed as follows when the interpreter starts:

If an environment variable APL_LIB_ROOT is defined, then its value is used
as library-root. Otherwise the path from the current directory (".") up to
the root directory ("/") is searched until a directory containing two
files 'workspaces' and 'wslib1' is found. Normally 'workspaces' and 'wslib1'
are directories, but for the computation of library-root files suffice.

If such a directory is found, then it is used as library-root; otherwise the
current directory (i.e. ".") is used and converted to an absolute path.

For example, if library-root is "." then the command

@example
)LOAD 2 test
@end example

will try to load the workspace file

./wslib2/test.xml

Using a library root implies that all 10 library directories are contained
in the same directory. This is good enough for single-user environments but
is often not adequate for multi-user environments where some directories
are not writable by users and different users have different home directories.

For that reason the above library root scheme can be overridden by the
GNU APL configuration files (preferences). In these files you can un-comment
any of the LIBREF-0 to LIBREF-9 settings (which correspond to library
numbers 0 to 9) and provide your own paths. The library numbers NOT overridden
in a 'preferences' file still follow the library root scheme.

