Naturally, this only works, iff:

@itemize
@item @b{xmodmap} is installed and working,
@item the current keyboard mapping was installed with @b{xmodmap},
@item no other keyboard mappings are in effect, and
@item the keycodes are correct (see below).
@end itemize

IOW: @b{]KEYB SCAN} troubleshoots the case
@i{correct keycode, but incorrect keysymbol(s)} above.

@node Subsubsection 2.11.3.4
@subsubsection ]KEYB USER

@b{]KEYB USER} does not try to figure the current keyboard mapping but rather
displays a static file provided by the user. This mode is a fallback for the 
case where the other modes are not able to produce a correct keyboard layout.
The user can take the output of @b{]KEYB GUESS} as a starting point and correct
the deviations from the actual keyboard layout.

The name of file shown with @b{]KEYB USER} can be configured in one of the
@b{preferences} files.

@node Subsubsection 2.11.3.5
@subsubsection ]KEYB GUESS

@b{]KEYB GUESS} does not try to figure the current keyboard mapping but rather
displays the layout that the various keyboard configuration files that are
shipped with GNU APL are likely to produce. The layout is a standard US APL
keyboard.

@node Subsubsection 2.11.3.6
@subsubsection Optional ]KEYB arguments

@b{]KEYB SCAN KEYS} does not run @b{xmodmap -pke} but rather shows how
the keys are supposed to be positioned on the keyboard. This shows how
@b{xmodmap -pke} assumes the keys are positioned. For example:

@example
      ]KEYB SCAN KEYS
US Keyboard Layout.    Source: GNU APL builtin" 

