@node Section 2.23
@section ⌹[X] - Miscellaneous Matrix and Vector Operations

@c ............................................................................
@node Subsection 2.23.1
@subsection ⌹[1] and ⌹[2] - QR Factorizations

@b{Z←⌹[1] B} and @b{Z←⌹[2] B} compute a QR factorization of the real or
complex matrix B. The results of @b{Z←⌹[1] B} and @b{Z←⌹[2] B} are
conceptually identical, while the algorithms used to compute the results
differ. Also, @b{Z←⌹[1] B} always exist, while @b{Z←⌹[2] B} requires
@b{libgsl} to be installed when GNU APL is compiled.

The axis argument @b{X} is used to either clear near-0 matrix items to
exactly 0.0 during the computation (in Garry Helzer's algorithm), or else
to select a different algorithm for computing the factorization. Set
@b{X←⎕CT} if unsure.

The result Z is a triple (Q R Ri)←Z with the following properties.
Let ⍴B=(M, N).

* @b{Q} is an orthogonal M×M matrix, i.e Q@sup{-1} = Q@sup{T}, and Q +.× ⍉Q
 is the M×M identity matrix I@sub{M} (with I@sub{M}←∘.=⍨⍳M).

* @b{R} is an upper triangular N×N matrix, i.e. R[m;n] = 0 for all n < m.
  Note that if M>N then, following a convention in other libraries (read:
  libgsl), the triangular matrices R and Ri have shape (N N) and not (M N).
  This is because the rows below row N are always 0 in R and in Ri, and
  are therefore not of interest. As a consequence, in order to restore
  B from Q and R one has to either use @b{Q+.×M N↑R} or else Q∘R (the latter
  accepts arguments R with fewer rows than columns of Q.

* @b{Ri} is the inverse of @b{R}, i.e. @b{Ri +.× R} is the N×N identity
  matrix I@sub{N}.

* @b{B = Q +.× M N↑R}.

Example 1 (real B)
@example
      ⊢B←3 3⍴ 1 1 3 2 4 2 4 8 7
1 1 3
2 4 2
4 8 7

      (Q R Ri)←⌹[⎕CT]B

