@node Section 2.25
@section Dyadic ⎕CR

The @b{⎕CR} function has now an optional left argument that selects one of
several formatting styles and conversion functions in addition to the
well-known monadic form.

Calling @b{⎕CR} monadically without an axis and with an empty right argument
shows a list of all functions provided by @b{⎕CR}:

@example
      ⎕CR ''
@end example

@b{Definition}: A @i{byte vector} is an integer (!) vector with numbers
having a (signed or unsigned) 8-bit value (i.e. a value from -128 to 255
inclusive). Such byte vectors are frequently used arguments and results
of @b{⎕FIO} functions.

Let @b{Z←A ⎕CR B}.

Then the left argument @b{A} of @b{⎕CR} selects one of several subfunctions
of @b{⎕CR}:

@itemize
@item @b{A∈0 1 2 3 4 7 8 9 29}: various formatting styles (boxed, 
      APL input/output, etc.).  Just try them out.

@item @b{A∈5 6}: convert byte vector B to a string of uppercase or lowercase
i     hex digits respectively. Every byte in @b{B} becomes 2 characters
      in @b{Z}.

@item @b{A=10}: convert variable named in @b{B} to an APL expression
      producing it.

@item @b{A=11}: convert value @b{B} to byte vector @b{Z} in CDR ("Common Data
      Representation", an IBM standard) format (similar to @b{3 ⎕TF}).

@item @b{A=12}: convert byte vector @b{B} in CDR format to value @b{Z}.

@item @b{A=13}: convert hex string @b{B} to byte vector @b{Z}.

If a conversion has an inverse conversion (like 12 being the inverse of 11)
then the inverse conversion can be expressed as the negative of the conversion
number. For example, @b{12 ⎕CR B} is the same as @b{¯11 ⎕CR B}.

@item @b{A=14}: conversion 11 followed by conversion 13 (Value to hex string
      in CDR format)

@item @b{A=15}: conversion 13 followed by conversion 12 (hex string in CDR
      format to Value)

@item @b{A=16}: encode byte vector B into @b{Z} (base64 encoding, @b{RFC 4648})

@item @b{A=17}: decode base64 vector @b{B} into byte vector @b{Z} (base64
      encoding, @b{RFC 4648})

@item @b{A=18}: convert text vector @b{B} into byte vector @b{Z} (UTF8 encoding,
      @b{RFC 3629}) 

@item @b{A=19}: convert byte vector B into text vector @b{Z} (UTF8 encoding,
      @b{RFC 3629})

@item @b{A=20-25}: like 3,4,i or 7-9 but using a formatting similar to
      NARS APL @b{⎕FMT} (showing the axis lengths as numbers instead of
      @b{→} and @b{↓})

@item @b{A=26}: @b{Z} is the cell types of the ravel elements of @b{B}, i.e.
      @itemize
      @item @b{2}: character,
      @item @b{16}: integer,
      @item @b{32}: real number,
      @item @b{64}: complex number.
@end itemize

@item @b{A=27}: Z[I] is the primary data representation (for example the
      real part  of a complex number, or the numerator of a rational number)
      of B[I].

@item @b{A=28}: Z[I] is the additional data representation (for example
      the imaginary part of a complex number, or the denominator of a
      rational number) of B[I].

@item @b{A=30}: @b{Z} is B with all top-level elements conformed to a common
      rank and shape (as required by the @b{⍤} operator). This conversion is
      primarily used  internally by the GNU APL interpreter.

@item @b{A∈31 32}: These conversions are used internally by @b{⎕INP}.

@item @b{A=33}: convert tagged byte vector to a TLV (Tag/Length/Value)
      buffer. The TLV buffer can be sent over a byte stream (socket) and
      easily decoded at the other end. Say @b{B = B[1], B[2], ..., B[n]} such
     that @b{B1} is an Integer (the tag) and @b{B[j]} is a character in the
     range 0-255 for j > 1.
     Let @b{Z←33 ⎕CR B} with @b{Z = Z[1], Z[2], ... Z[m]}. Then @b{Z[1 2 3 4]}
     is the 4 byte tag, @b{Z[5 6 7 8]} is the 4 byte data length
     (n-1) = (m - 8), and @b{1↓B == 8 ↓ Z}. In other words, the first 4 bytes
     of @b{Z} are the tag in big endian byte order, the next 4 bytes are the
     length of @b{B} except the tag, and the rest of @b{Z} is @b{B} except
     the tag.

Example:
@example
      Tag←55   ⍝ hex 37
      5 ⎕CR 33 ⎕CR Tag,'Value'
000000370000000556616C7565
@end example

@item @b{A=34}: this is the inverse of @b{33 ⎕CR}. The intended use for
@b{33 ⎕CR} and @b{34 ⎕CR} is the transmission of a tagged byte vector over
e.g a TCP socket:

@verbatim
  Sender                                              Receiver
  ──────                                              ────────
  T,Data →→→ 33 ⎕CR T,Data   →→→ TCP connection →→→   34 ⎕CR T,Data →→→ T,Data
@end verbatim

Example:
@example
      34 ⎕CR ¯5 ⎕CR '000000370000000556616C7565'
55 Value
@end example

The TLVs constructed by @b{33 ⎕CR} by the sender and decoded with
@b{34 ⎕CR} by the receiver can be sent back-to-back over a TCP connection
or similar in such a way that the receiver knows exactly after which byte
a TLV ends (and possibly the next TLV, if any, starts). This is perfect
for connections over which data is sent sporadically. @b{33 ⎕CR} and
@b{34 ⎕CR} are particularly useful for encoding and decoding TLV byte
buffers exchanged between GNU APL and processes that were forked by
GNU APL with @b{⎕FIO[57]} (aka. @b{fork()} and @b{execve()}).

@item @b{A=35}: convert a string of lines (containing LF characters as line
      delimiters) to a nested vector of lines.

@item @b{A=36}: the inverse of @b{⎕CR[35]}. Convert a nested vector of lines
      to a string with lines terminated with LF characxters.

@item @b{A=37}: Same as @b{⎕CR B} but without removing any indentation.

@item @b{A=38}: Return an empty structured variable with (integer)
      capacity @b{Bi}, or convert an N×2 matrix @b{B} to a structured variable.

@item @b{A=39}: convert a strucured variable @b{B} to an N×2 variable.

@item @b{A=40}: pack a boolean variable Bi (experimental).

@item @b{A=41}: unpack a boolean variable Bi (experimental).

@item @b{A=42}: tokenize the APL statement Bs.

@item @b{A=43}: parse the APL statement Bs.

@item @b{A=44}: decode the (integer) token tag B or the (nested) token B.
@end itemize

Most dyadic @b{⎕CR} variants whose argument @b{B} is expected to be a byte
vector throw:

@itemize
@item RANK ERROR if 1≠⍴⍴B
@item DOMAIN ERROR if one of the B[j] is not a proper byte value
@end itemize

A proper byte value is either an integer in the range -128...255 inclusive,
or a (Unicode) character with a code point between U+FF80 and U+FFFF
(inclusive, corresponding to a negative signed char in C/C++) or between
U+0000...U+00FF (inclusive, corresponding to an unsigned char or to a signed
positive char in C/C++). Real, Complex, or rational numbers are never proper
byte values even if their value is close to an integer. Nor are nested APL
values or values being assigned.

@b{⎕CR} is a function group, therefore its subfunctions can be selected with
a name. For example: monadic @b{⎕CR.hex_to_bytes} is the same as monadic
@b{⎕CR[13]} or dyadic @b{13 ⎕CR}.

@c ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node Section 2.26
@section  Dyadic ⎕FX (Native Functions)

A Native Function is a function that can be called in APL like a normal user
defined APL function, but is implemented in C++.

A native function is created with A ⎕FX B. A is a string that is the
path of a shared library and B is the name of the function in APL.

The GNU APL package contains a shared library file_io.so that contains the
implementation of a native function for reading and writing files (fopen(),
fclose(), ...), For example:

@example
      ⍝ fix native function in lib_file_io.so as FILE_IO
      ⍝
      'lib_file_io.so' ⎕FX 'FILE_IO'
FILE_IO

      ⍝ show overview of subfunctions in FILE_IO
      ⍝
      FILE_IO ''
   Functions provided by this library.
   Assumes 'lib_file_io.so'  ⎕FX  'FUN'

   Legend: e - error code
           i - integer
           h - file handle (integer)
           s - string
           A1, A2, ...  nested vector with elements A1, A2, ...

           FUN     ''    print this text on stderr
        '' FUN     ''    print this text on stdout
           FUN[ 0] ''    print this text on stderr
        '' FUN[ 0] ''    print this text on stdout

   Zi ←    FUN[ 1] ''    errno (of last call)
   Zs ←    FUN[ 2] Be    strerror(Be)
   Zh ← As FUN[ 3] Bs    fopen(Bs, As) filename Bs mode As
   Zh ←    FUN[ 3] Bs    fopen(Bs, "r") filename Bs
      ...
@end example

Recent versions of GNU APL have replaced the native FILE_IO function above by
the system function ⎕FIO. ⎕FIO need not be ⎕FX'ed and is otherwise backward
compatible to the native function. New function numbers are, however, only
added to ⎕FIO and not to the old native function FILE_IO. The parameters of
the functions are described in the man pages for, e.g. strerror, fopen, ...
and are fairly obvious.

Many functions in FILE_IO have byte vectors as arguments or return byte 
vectors. A byte vector is an integer vector whose numbers fit into a byte
(so they are integers between -128 and 255). Often ⎕UCS and the functions in
dyadic ⎕CR are used to convert such byte vectors to/from, for example,
Unicode strings.

The GNU APL package also contains other shared libraries as templates
for your own native functions. Copy one of the files
src/native/template_F0.cc (for niladic native functions),
src/native/template_F12.cc (for nomadic native functions),
src/native/template_OP1.cc (for monadic native operators),
or src/native/template_OP2/cc (for dyadic native operators) to your own
.cc file and adjust src/native/Makefile.am accordingly.

Note: The )IN and )OUT commands of GNU APL support native functions, but
to do so they have to use dyadic ⎕FX. This renders the workspace
interchange file (.atf files) written by )OUT incompatible with all other
APL interpreters if the workspace contains native functions. The )OUT 
command prints a warning when it is used with a workspace that contains
native functions.

Note: As of GNU APL 1.6, the native function FILE_IO has been turned into the
system function ⎕FIO. The syntax of ⎕FIO is the same as for FILE_IO. The
)CLEAR workspace command will close all open files. 


