@node Section 5.7
@section GNU APL Vector Notation

With the definitions from the previous section we can explain how GNU APL
has implemented vector notation:

1. GNU APL distinguishes between literal and mixed strands. literal strands
   are combined into a single APL value at tokenization time. This is a
   very effective optimization (which can be disabled at @b{./configure}
   time). In contrast, mixed strands are created at phrase matching time, i.e.
   when an APL expression is evaluated. The tokenizatio of APL expressions
   happens only once, while phrase matching occurs every time when a
   statement is being executed and therefore moving major parts of the strand
   building from phrase matching time to tokenization time can bring
   substantial performance benefits.

2. The tokenization expands simple APL primitives with literal arguments and
   short results into their literal equivalent. Currently the APL primitives
   @b{N⍴B}, @b{N/B}, @b{N⌿B}, @b{,B}, @b{⍪B}, and @b{⊂B} are handled this way.

3. The tokenization of literal strands has dedicated code for literal
   arguments of the power (@b{⍣}) and rank operators (@b{⍤}) to make make
   it working like described in the ISO standard. This is, in contrast to
   defined operators, possible because the ISO standard defines in very
   detail how its right operand needs to look like and how deviations shall
   be handled (@b{DOMAIN ERROR}, @b{LENGTH ERROR} etc.

4. The phrase matching of mixed strands builds the strand step-by-step
   according to the following rules:

@itemize
@item two adjacent APL scalars @b{A} and @b{B} create a new open strand
      (with two strand items). Each of the two scalars @b{A} or @b{B} can
      be simple (like numbers or single characters) or nested (like strings
      or closed strands).
@item An APL scalar @b{A} adjacent to an open strand @b{B} preprends @b{A}
      to @b{B}.  That is, @b{B←A, B}.
@item An open strand @b{A} adjacent to an an APL scalar @b{B} appends @b{B} 
      to @b{A}.  That is, @b{A←A, B}.
@item the previous two rules prevent two adjacent open strands, because the
      strand items of a potential open left strand @b{A} are prepended item
      by item to an open right strand @b{B} (which prevents the creation of a
      new open left strand while an open right strand exists,

@item Like the normal APL evaluation, this procedure is preformed from the
      right to the left.
@item if an open strand hits a closing parenthesis then a new phrase matching
      context is created in which the current procedure is abandoned until
      the corresponding opening parentheses has been processed. The result
      of the expression in parentheses is then taken as the next strand item
      for the abandoned strand (if any).
@item Any symbols encountered during this procedure are being resolved into
      scalars (possibly enclosing them if they are not). Niladic functions are
      called to obtain their result.
@item Likewise, any literal strands that were created at tokenization time
      are considered closed (which cause them to be enclosed when preprended
      or appended to an open mixed strand).
@item If a strand is open then any other token (functions, operators,
      brackets, end-of-statement, etc.) closes it. The result is a single
      value for the strand.
@end itemize

5. The operators @b{⍣} (power operator) and @b{⍤} (rank operator), whose
   right operand can be identified by the rules given in @b{iso}) have
   dedicated code that "unstrands" the right operand from a strand that
   may have been mistakenly created in @b{3.} above.

@c @node Subsection 5.7.1
@subsection Example

Consider the following APL statement:

@example
      ∇FOO
       "Time is now: " ⎕TS
      ∇
@end example

When function @b{FOO} is created its single function line is being tokenized.
The tokenization of the function line sees the string "Time is now: " which
is a literal token wth 13 literal items (= single characters). The result of
the tokenization is therefore 2 tokens: the string and the system function
@b{⎕TS}. Naturally @b{⎕TS} is the time stamp when function @b{FOO} is called
and not the the time when function @b{FOO} is created. Therefore the strand
building stops at this point and leaves the string as an (incomplete) strand
because the strand building can not predict when @b{FOO} will be called. At
this point the incomplete strand and the system function @b{⎕TS} will become
adjacent tokens in the function body of @b{FOO}.

Later on (or maybe never) @b{FOO} will be called. The execution of @b{FOO}
(which goes from  right to left) first sees the niladic token @b{⎕TS}, and
evaluates it to an integer vector @b{B}, say @b{2026 1 1 18 5 6 194}. Values
returned from functions, values of variables, and the literal strands from
the tokenization are all closed and incomplete, and so is @b{B} at this point.
The execution then fetches the next token @b{A}, which is the string. The
two adjacent tokens @b{A} and @b{B} now match the pattern @b{A B} in the
phrase table of the interpreter. The corresponding phrase evaluator for
that pattern then prepends the items in @b{A} to @b{B} and replaces the
two tokens @b{A} and @b{B} with the new (single) token for the modified @b{B}.
The next token is then an @b{END} (for end of staement) token which causes
@b{B} to be printed.

@b{A final remark}: It should be noted, that the phrase table defined 
in @b{iso} is somewhat incomplete. In particular the pattern @b{A B}
above (which performs the strand building in the execution phase) is
not present in @b{iso}. Also, @b{iso} defines @b{END} tokens as used
above, but no pattern in ehich they appear. All this has the unfortunate
consequence that vector notation is provided by every APL interpreter,
but the details of it differ considerably. For example, @b{1 2 3[2]} could
be @b{2} in one interpreter, but raise a @b{RANK ERROR} in another. Even
for different interpreters od the same vendor. The only reliable way to
write portable APL programs is to use (otherwise redundant) parentheses,
in particular around operators and their operands, and around strands that
are being indexed.


